 widely erased and obfuscated. Telling this history requires a tangled balance of contextualizing the past and reporting on the present, of respecting a culture even while feeling lost within it. We Are All Armenian brings together established and emerging Armenian authors to reflect on the complications of Armenian ethnic identity today. These personal essays elevate diasporic voices that have been historically silenced inside and outside of their communities, including queer, multiracial, and multiethnic writers. The eighteen contributors to this contemporary anthology explore issues of displacement, assimilation, inheritance, and broader definitions of home. Through engaging creative nonfiction, many of them question what it is to be Armenian enough inside an often unacknowledged community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArmenian diaspora. 0aArmeniansxSocial life and customs. 0aArmenianszNorth AmericavBiography. 0aArmenianszNorth AmericaxEthnic identity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aArmenia, ethnic identity, immigrants, immigrant identity, Armenian studies.  aArmenian diaspora, diaspora, Armenian Genocide, acknowledgment, intersectionality, displacement.  ainheritance, assimilation, Armenian American.1 aAgabian, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAghajanian, Liana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmen, Sophia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvakian, Kohar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBohjalian, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoudjikanian, Raffy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDer Boghossian, J. P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato